problem:
Let \[f(n) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
n^2-2 & \text{ if }n<0, \\
2n-20 & \text{ if }n \geq 0.
\end{array}
\right.\]What is the positive difference between the two values of $a$ that satisfy the equation $f(-2)+f(2)+f(a)=0$?

solution:
All points on the line $x=-3$ are of the form $(-3,y)$, where $y$ is a real number.  The distance from $(5,2)$ to $(-3,y)$ is $$\sqrt{(5-(-3))^2+(2-y)^2}$$ units.  Setting this expression equal to 10, we find \begin{align*}
\sqrt{(5-(-3))^2+(2-y)^2}&= 10 \\
64+(2-y)^2&= 100 \\
(2-y)^2&= 36 \\
2-y&=\pm 6 \\
y=2\pm6.
\end{align*} The product of $2+6 = 8$ and $2-6 = -4$ is $\boxed{-32}$. [asy]

